      "title": "The Dispute Over Which Bloods Invalidate the Sacrifice: Rabbi Akiva, the Rabbis, and Rabbi Eliezer",
      "display_title": "Blood Invalidation",
      "timestamp": "00:26",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction to the Three Opinions on Blood Entering the Sanctuary",
          "display_title": "Three Opinions",
          "timestamp": "00:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Akiva's Derivation from the Double Language of 'All Sin Offerings'",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Akiva's Logic",
          "timestamp": "01:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Rabbis Limit the Rule to Sin Offerings Only; Rabbi Eliezer Adds Guilt Offerings",
          "display_title": "Rabbis vs. R. Eliezer",
          "timestamp": "02:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rava's Explanation of the Rabbis' Position: Why Not the Guilt Offering?",
      "display_title": "Rava's Reasoning",
      "timestamp": "03:17",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rava: The Guilt Offering Has No Specific Source, Only a Kal va-Chomer from the Olah",
          "display_title": "Rava's Answer",
          "timestamp": "03:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Testing the Kal va-Chomer: Olah is Completely Burnt but Blood Entering Doesn't Disqualify",
          "display_title": "Failed Kal va-Chomer",
          "timestamp": "03:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Refutation: Olah is Not an Atonement Offering, So the Logic Breaks Down",
          "display_title": "Refuting Olah Logic",
          "timestamp": "05:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Attempt to Learn from the Meal Offering of a Sinner; Rejected Due to Different Process",
          "display_title": "Meal Offering Attempt",
          "timestamp": "06:23"
        },
        {
          "title": "Back to the Olah: The Gemara Establishes That Neither Resembles the Other Perfectly",
          "display_title": "Kal va-Chomer Fails",
          "timestamp": "08:19"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Finding the Common Ground: Both Olah and Chatat Are Kodshei Kodashim",
      "display_title": "Kodshei Kodashim",
      "timestamp": "08:36",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Common Feature: Both Olah and Chatat Are Kodshei Kodashim (Most Holy)",
          "display_title": "Holiness Level",
          "timestamp": "08:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "Asham Also Qualifies as Kodshei Kodashim, But Introducing a Different Distinction",
          "display_title": "Asham Classification",
          "timestamp": "09:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "Distinguishing Factor: Only Asham Has a Prescribed Minimum Value",
          "display_title": "Asham's Minimum",
          "timestamp": "10:28"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Deriving the Rabbis' Position from the Verses: Dam (Blood) and the Pronoun Damah",
      "display_title": "Verse Interpretation",
      "timestamp": "11:17",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Word Damah (Its Blood) Teaches: It Is the Blood of This Offering, Not Another's",
          "display_title": "Damah Pronoun",
          "timestamp": "11:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Eliezer's Reading: Damah Teaches That It Is Blood, Not Flesh",
          "display_title": "R. Eliezer's Read",
          "timestamp": "11:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Rabbis' Additional Lesson: The Verse Limits the Rule to Chatat Alone",
          "display_title": "Rabbis' Limit",
          "timestamp": "12:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Eliezer Does Not Interpret the Double Language This Way",
          "display_title": "R. Eliezer Differs",
          "timestamp": "13:08"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Connecting Asham to Chatat Through the Mincha: Learning Similar Laws Across Offerings",
      "display_title": "Mincha Connection",
      "timestamp": "13:54",
      "micro_segments": [
